  "prompt": "What is the acceptable TDS level of drinking water?",
  "response": "The acceptable **Total Dissolved Solids (TDS)** level in drinking water varies depending on guidelines set by different organizations. Here are the general recommendations:\n\n1. **World Health Organization (WHO):**  \n   - Acceptable TDS level: **Up to 300 mg/L**.  \n   - Maximum permissible TDS level: **Up to 600 mg/L**.\n\n2. **U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA):**  \n   - No strict enforceable limit but recommends a TDS level of **500 mg/L** for drinking water.\n\n3. **Bureau of Indian Standards (BIS):**  \n   - Acceptable TDS level: **Up to 500 mg/L**.  \n   - Permissible limit in the absence of alternative sources: **Up to 2000 mg/L**.\n\n### TDS Levels and Water Quality:\n- **0\u2013300 mg/L:** Excellent for drinking.  \n- **300\u2013600 mg/L:** Good for drinking but may have a slightly salty taste.  \n- **600\u2013900 mg/L:** Fair; may not be ideal for regular consumption.  \n- **900\u20131200 mg/L:** Poor; not recommended for drinking.  \n- **Above 1200 mg/L:** Unacceptable for drinking.\n\nA TDS level below **500 mg/L** is generally considered safe and palatable. However, the suitability of water also depends on the types of dissolved solids (e.g., minerals, salts, or contaminants). If you're unsure about your water quality, you can test it using a TDS meter or send a sample to a certified lab for analysis.",
